'''Jesus Day''' is a common term for the day of the [[March for Jesus]] held annually by some Christians on the Saturday before [[Pentecost Sunday]], since the 1980s, with the purpose of "express[ing] their love for [[Jesus]] by serving their communities and worshiping their Lord in the streets of their cities."<ref>{{cite web | title =Jesus Day | work =March for Jesus | url =http://www.marchforjesususa.com/usa/index.htm | accessdate =2007-07-24 | deadurl =yes | archiveurl =https://archive.is/20120904132158/http://www.marchforjesususa.com/usa/index.htm | archivedate =2012-09-04 | df = }}</ref>
While [[List of Governors of Texas|Governor]] of [[Texas]], Former [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]], signed a bill into law proclaiming June 10, 2000 to be ''Jesus Day,'' the event was observed in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] that year. The Texas proclamation urged people to "follow the example of Jesus" to "answer the call to serve those in need". The proclamation received national attention when the ''[[New York Times]]'' ran an article on it.<ref>{{cite news | title =Jesus Day | work =THE 2000 CAMPAIGN: THE RELIGION ISSUE; Bush's Jesus Day Is Called Insensitive and a Violation of the First Amendment | url =https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CEFD8123CF935A3575BC0A9669C8B63&scp=1&sq=%22jesus+day%22&st=nyt | accessdate =2008-02-10 | first=Laurie | last=Goodstein | date=2000-08-06}}</ref>
