{{Main|Country music|List of music festivals}} {{sidebar | title = Country music festivals |image =[[File:Boots & Hearts Festival, 2012.jpg|290px]] |headingstyle = background:lightgrey; | heading1 = Related genres | content1 = [[Country music]], [[folk music]], [[country rock]], [[country pop]], [[bluegrass music]] | heading2 = Related events | content2 =[[:Category:Music festivals]], [[concert tour]], [[music festival]], [[folk festivals]], [[rock festival]], [[bluegrass music festivals]], [[old-time music festivals]], [[free festival]], [[jam band festivals]], [[rodeo]], [[barn dance]] }}
The following is an '''incomplete list of country music festivals,''' which encapsulates [[music festivals]] focused on [[country music]]. This list may have some overlap with the larger topic '''[[list of folk festivals]]''', and may also overlap with the related topics '''[[list of blues festivals]]''', '''[[list of jam band music festivals]]''', '''[[list of bluegrass music festivals]]''', and '''[[list of old-time music festivals]]'''. Many of the festivals take place in North America.
Country music is a genre of [[American popular music]] that originated in [[Southern United States]], in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] in the 1920s,<ref name="Peterson">{{cite book| author = Richard A. Peterson| title = Creating Country Music: Fabricating Authenticity| date = 1999-12-15| publisher = University of Chicago Press| isbn = 978-0-226-66285-5| page = 9 }}</ref> and It takes its roots from the southeastern genre of [[American folk music]] and [[Western music (North America)|Western music]]. The origins of country music are the folk music of mostly white, [[working-class Americans]], who blended popular songs, Irish and Celtic fiddle tunes, traditional ballads, and cowboy songs, and various musical traditions from European immigrant communities.<ref>ARRP Bulletin. Vol. 53 No 1. "50&nbsp;Minutes on the Road. Betsy Tower. page 50. citing Commuting in America III and Arbitron.</ref> [[barn dance|Barn dancing]] and other [[folk dance]] styles would be featured at country music gatherings, and many modern festivals have continued to feature dance, [[rodeo]], or other cultural aspects.
The term ''country music'' gained popularity in the 1940s in preference to the earlier term [[hillbilly]] music, it came to encompass [[Western music (North America)|Western music]], which evolved parallel to hillbilly music from similar roots, in the mid-20th century. The term ''country music'' is used today to describe many [[List of country genres|styles]] and subgenres, and festivals may focus on [[Americana (music)|Americana]] genres such as [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], or newer genres such as [[country rock]], [[country pop]], or [[alternative country]].
